For instance, this way one finds the power series for complex powers of the Lambert function.

=== Power series in several variables ===
Formal power series in any number of indeterminates (even infinitely many) can be defined. If &quot;I&quot; is an index set and &quot;XI&quot; is the set of indeterminates &quot;Xi&quot; for &quot;i&quot;∈&quot;I&quot;, then a monomial &quot;X&quot;&quot;α&quot; is any finite product of elements of &quot;XI&quot; (repetitions allowed); a formal power series in &quot;XI&quot; with coefficients in a ring &quot;R&quot; is determined by any mapping from the set of monomials &quot;X&quot;&quot;α&quot; to a corresponding coefficient &quot;c&quot;&quot;α&quot;, and is denoted formula_352. The set of all such formal power series is denoted formula_353 and it is given a ring structure by defining

:formula_354

and

:formula_355

==== Topology ====
The topology on formula_356 is such that a sequence of its elements converges only if for each monomial &quot;X&quot;α the corresponding coefficient stabilizes. If &quot;I&quot; is finite, then this the &quot;J&quot;-adic topology, where &quot;J&quot; is the ideal of formula_356 generated by all the indeterminates in &quot;XI&quot;. This does not hold if &quot;I&quot; is infinite. For example, if formula_358 then the sequence formula_359 with formula_360 does not converge with respect to any &quot;J&quot;-adic topology on &quot;R&quot;, but clearly for each monomial the corresponding coefficient stabilizes.

As remarked above, the topology on a repeated formal power series ring like formula_361 is usually chosen in such a way that it becomes isomorphic as a topological ring to formula_362

====Operations====
All of the operations defined for series in one variable may be extended to the several variables case.

* A series is invertible if and only if its constant term is invertible in &quot;R&quot;.
* The composition &quot;f&quot;(&quot;g&quot;(&quot;X&quot;)) of two series &quot;f&quot; and &quot;g&quot; is defined if &quot;f&quot; is a series in a single indeterminate, and the constant term of &quot;g&quot; is zero. For a series &quot;f&quot; in several indeterminates a form of &quot;composition&quot; can similarly be defined, with as many separate series in the place of &quot;g&quot; as there are indeterminates.

In the case of the formal derivative, there are now separate partial derivative operators, which differentiate with respect to each of the indeterminates. They all commute with each other.

==== Universal property ====
In the several variables case, the universal property characterizing formula_363 becomes the following. If &quot;S&quot; is a commutative associative algebra over &quot;R&quot;, if &quot;I&quot; is an ideal of &quot;S&quot; such that the &quot;I&quot;-adic topology on &quot;S&quot; is complete, and if &quot;x&quot;1, ..., &quot;xr&quot; are elements of &quot;I&quot;, then there is a &quot;unique&quot; map formula_364 with the following properties:

* Φ is an &quot;R&quot;-algebra homomorphism
* Φ is continuous
* Φ(&quot;X&quot;&quot;i&quot;) = &quot;x&quot;&quot;i&quot; for &quot;i&quot; = 1, ..., &quot;r&quot;.

===Non-commuting variables===
The several variable case can be further generalised by taking &quot;non-commuting variables&quot; &quot;Xi&quot; for &quot;i&quot; ∈ &quot;I&quot;, where &quot;I&quot; is an index set and then a monomial &quot;X&quot;α is any word in the &quot;XI&quot;; a formal power series in &quot;XI&quot; with coefficients in a ring &quot;R&quot; is determined by any mapping from the set of monomials &quot;X&quot;α to a corresponding coefficient &quot;c&quot;α, and is denoted formula_365. The set of all such formal power series is denoted &quot;R&quot;«&quot;XI&quot;», and it is given a ring structure by defining addition pointwise

:formula_366

and multiplication by

:formula_367

where · denotes concatenation of words. These formal power series over &quot;R&quot; form the Magnus ring over &quot;R&quot;.

=== On a semiring ===
Given an alphabet formula_368 and a semiring formula_111. The formal power series over formula_111 supported on the language formula_371 is denoted by formula_372. It consists of all mappings formula_373, where formula_371 is the free monoid generated by the non-empty set formula_368.

The elements of formula_372 can be written as formal sums

:formula_377

where formula_378 denotes the value of formula_379 at the word formula_380. The elements formula_381 are called the coefficients of formula_379.

For formula_383 the support of formula_379 is the set

:formula_385

A series where every coefficient is either formula_386 or formula_387 is called the characteristic series of its support.

The subset of formula_372 consisting of all series with a finite support is denoted by formula_389 and called polynomials.

For formula_390 and formula_391, the sum formula_392 is defined by 
:formula_393
The (Cauchy) product formula_394 is defined by
:formula_395
The Hadamard product formula_396 is defined by
:formula_397
And the products by a scalar formula_398 and formula_399 by
:formula_400 and formula_401, respectively.

With these operations formula_402 and formula_403 are semirings, where formula_404 is the empty word in formula_371.

These formal power series are used to model the behavior of weighted automata, in theoretical computer science, when the coefficients formula_378 of the series are taken to be the weight of a path with label formula_407 in the automata.

===Replacing the index set by an ordered abelian group===
Suppose formula_408 is an ordered abelian group, meaning an abelian group with a total ordering formula_409 respecting the group&#x27;s addition, so that formula_410. Let I be a well-ordered subset of formula_408, meaning I contains no infinite descending chain. Consider the set consisting of

:formula_412

for all such I, with formula_413 in a commutative ring formula_5, where we assume that for any index set, if all of the formula_413 are zero then the sum is zero. Then formula_416 is the ring of formal power series on formula_408; because of the condition that the indexing set be well-ordered the product is well-defined, and we of course assume that two elements which differ by zero are the same. Sometimes the notation formula_418 is used to denote formula_416.

Various properties of formula_5 transfer to formula_416. If formula_5 is a field, then so is formula_416. If formula_5 is an ordered field, we can order formula_416 by setting any element to have the same sign as its leading coefficient, defined as the least element of the index set I associated to a non-zero coefficient. Finally if formula_408 is a divisible group and formula_5 is a real closed field, then formula_416 is a real closed field, and if formula_5 is algebraically closed, then so is formula_416.

This theory is due to Hans Hahn, who also showed that one obtains subfields when the number of (non-zero) terms is bounded by some fixed infinite cardinality.

==Examples and related topics==
* Bell series are used to study the properties of multiplicative arithmetic functions
* Formal groups are used to define an abstract group law using formal power series
* Puiseux series are an extension of formal Laurent series, allowing fractional exponents
* Rational series

== See also ==
* Ring of restricted power series

